{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem requires finding the shortest bitstring length N such that no two given bitstrings (of varying lengths) are prefixes of each other after being extended to length N, while also satisfying a specific constraint regarding the number of possible bitstrings. This is essentially a problem of finding the minimum depth of a Trie that satisfies prefix-free properties and capacity constraints.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "trie_construction",
      "instructions": "Construct a Trie from the given set of bitstrings. Identify all nodes that are either terminal nodes (end of a given string) or have descendants that are terminal nodes. These nodes represent 'conflicts' if they are prefixes of each other."
    },
    {
      "label": "conflict_analysis",
      "instructions": "For each given bitstring, determine the minimum length it must be extended to so that it is not a prefix of any other given bitstring. Specifically, find the depth of the first node in the Trie that branches away from the path of the current string or reaches a leaf that is not a prefix of another."
    },
    {
      "label": "capacity_constraint_check",
      "instructions": "Given a target length N, calculate the maximum number of unique bitstrings of length N that can exist such that no given bitstring is a prefix of another. This involves calculating 2^(N - depth) for various branches in the Trie and ensuring the total capacity meets the problem's requirements (if applicable) or simply finding the smallest N that accommodates the prefix-free requirement."
    },
    {
      "label": "binary_search_for_N",
      "instructions": "Perform a binary search on the possible values of N (from the maximum length of a given string up to a reasonable upper bound like 60 or 100). For a candidate N, use the results from the Trie and conflict analysis to check if all strings can be extended to length N without violating the prefix-free property."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the Trie structure and conflict analysis to determine the minimum length required for each string to be unique. Use the capacity check to ensure the chosen N allows for the required number of distinct IDs. The final answer is the smallest N that satisfies both the prefix-free condition for all input strings and the total capacity constraint."
}
```

